That said, what libraries with icons included in Windows are the documented? I recall moricons.dll from Windows 3.1, which is still included with Windows 10, but I don't know if it's contractual or just a compatibility concession. Also, I remember when Windows Vista broke the icon ordering of shell32.dll. It was restored in Windows 7 (somewhat) and is kept unchanged up to Windows 10, but the fact that Vista broke it makes me guess that it never was contractual.
As Joshua says, it's a pain being unable to permanently embed icons in shortcuts. It made sense back in 1995, when it...Read moreThat said, what libraries with icons included in Windows are the documented? I recall moricons.dll from Windows 3.1, which is still included with Windows 10, but I don‚Äôt know if it‚Äôs contractual or just a compatibility concession. Also, I remember when Windows Vista broke the icon ordering of shell32.dll. It was restored in Windows 7 (somewhat) and is kept unchanged up to Windows 10, but the fact that Vista broke it makes me guess that it never was contractual.
As Joshua says, it‚Äôs a pain being unable to permanently embed icons in shortcuts. It made sense back in 1995, when it was nice to fit a shortcut file in a single 512 byte sector, but things have changed a lot since then. True, you can build your own icon library, but few people know that it‚Äôs possible or even have the right tools to do it. Even extracting an icon from a library into an .ico file is black magic for most users.
It could be greatly mitigated if Windows included its own documented icon library with a set of useful icons. A good start would be a subset of shell32.dll and moricons.dll (removing the ones for vintage DOS applications). Just name it ‚Äúicons.dll‚Äù and place it in the Windows directory, and users hunting around for icons will find it immediately.
